rComments: a bit dated. hard to understand what his expectations are for each exam. you might think you did well and end up with a not so great mark. his grading scheme is excellent though - affords you many opportunities to do well. 4 tests throughout the year;2 essays; participation grade is of course arbitrary and there is no accountability.
He's a very nice man. Always willing to help, but does just regurgitate the readings. Sadly, he's not the only Prof at U of T that does that.

Just totally useless. Not a good professor whatsoever. Disorganized, frequently forgetting to mark assignments etc. The subject matter that would have been interesting (Cdn Political Parties) turned out to be not very interesting at all.

What a painful class this is.  This prof is disorganized, boring, and often regurgitates the texts. There are way too many readings and they're from about 8 different textbooks. I had to force myself to stay awake.  What a mess.  It's a shame it's one of the few Cdn Politics classes at the university.
Nice professor, but a bit disorganized. Good use of guest lecturers.
This class actually made me interested in Canadian political parties! Good prof, fair exams, lots of interesting guest speakers and interesting essay choices

Greatest Prof - obviously not a uoft prof and that is sooooo refreshing! Kind, helpful, and understanding - it's not his fault the material is dry, look at the course content!!! Give us Professor Stein for good! He is the best

He's on loan from McMaster - Please take him back! His lecture style is the worst I've ever encountered. His lectures have no flow and don't seem to go anywhere, I can never tell what his main points are and he cannot effectivly summarize any theories. AVOID!
